   1  ''' 
   2  A Graph class implementation. The aim for this implementation is 
   3  1. To reflect implementation methods in literature as much as possible 
   4  3. To have something close to a "classic" object-oriented design 
   5  (compared to previous versions) 
   6   
   7  This implementation can be considered as a compromise between a graph 
   8  class designed for visualization and an efficient graph data structure. 
   9   
  10  One deviation from standard Graph implementations is to keep in neighbors in 
  11  an other adjacency list. We do this for efficiency reasons considering 
  12  traversing residual graphs. 
  13   
  14  We have a class for Graph and a class for Node. Edges are not represented as 
  15  objects. They are kept in a dictionary which also keeps their attributes. 
  16   
  17  Graph display related methods are inspired from Pydot. They are re-written 
  18  considering GIMPy needs. We also borrow two methods from Pydot, see 
  19  global_constants.py for details. 
  20   
  21  Default graph type is an undirected graph. 
  22   
  23  No custom exception will raise when the user tries to get in_neighbors of an 
  24  undirected graph. She should be aware of this. Python will raise an exception 
  25  since user is trying to read an attribute that does not exits. 
  26   
  27  Methods that implement algorithms has display argument in their API. If this 
  28  argument is not specified global display setting will be used for display 
  29  purposes of the algorithm method implements. You can use display argument to 
  30  get visualization of algorithm without changing global display behavior of your 
  31  Graph/Tree object. 
  32   
  33  Method documentation strings are orginized as follows. 
  34  API: method_name(arguments) 
  35  Description: Description of the method. 
  36  Input: Arguments and their explanation. 
  37  Pre: Necessary class attributes that should exists, methods to be called 
  38       before this method. 
  39  Post: Class attributes changed within the method. 
  40  Return: Return value of the method. 
  41   
  42  TODO(aykut): 
  43  -> svg display mode 
  44  -> label_strong_components() API change. Check backward compatibilty. 
  45  -> dfs should use search()? 
  46  -> display mode svg is not supported. 
  47  future: 
  48  -> The solution we find is not strongly feasible. Fix this. 
  49  '''

 631 -    def to_string(self): 

 632          ''' 
 633          API: to_string(self) 
 634          Description: 
 635          This method is based on pydot Graph class with the same name. 
 636          Returns a string representation of the graph in dot language. 
 637          It will return the graph and all its subelements in string form. 
 638          Return: 
 639              String that represents graph in dot language. 
 640          ''' 
 641          graph = list() 
 642          processed_edges = {} 
 643          graph.append('%s %s {\n' %(self.graph_type, self.name)) 
 644          for a in self.attr: 
 645              if a not in GRAPH_ATTRIBUTES: 
 646                  continue 
 647              val = self.attr[a] 
 648              if val is not None: 
 649                  graph.append( '%s=%s' % (a, quote_if_necessary(val)) ) 
 650              else: 
 651                  graph.append(a) 
 652              graph.append( ';\n' ) 
 653          # clusters 
 654          for c in self.cluster: 
 655              graph.append('subgraph cluster_%s {\n' %c) 
 656              for a in self.cluster[c]['attrs']: 
 657                  if a=='label': 
 658                      graph.append(a+'='+quote_if_necessary(self.cluster[c]['attrs'][a])+';\n') 
 659                      continue 
 660                  graph.append(a+'='+self.cluster[c]['attrs'][a]+';\n') 
 661              if len(self.cluster[c]['node_attrs'])!=0: 
 662                  graph.append('node [') 
 663              for a in self.cluster[c]['node_attrs']: 
 664                  graph.append(a+'='+self.cluster[c]['node_attrs'][a]) 
 665                  graph.append(',') 
 666              if len(self.cluster[c]['node_attrs'])!=0: 
 667                  graph.pop() 
 668                  graph.append('];\n') 
 669              # process cluster nodes 
 670              for n in self.cluster[c]['node_list']: 
 671                  data = self.get_node(n).to_string() 
 672                  graph.append(data + ';\n') 
 673              # process cluster edges 
 674              for n in self.cluster[c]['node_list']: 
 675                  for m in self.cluster[c]['node_list']: 
 676                      if self.check_edge(n,m): 
 677                          data = self.edge_to_string((n,m)) 
 678                          graph.append(data + ';\n') 
 679                          processed_edges[(n,m)]=None 
 680              graph.append('}\n') 
 681          # process remaining (non-cluster) nodes 
 682          for n in self.neighbors: 
 683              for c in self.cluster: 
 684                  if n in self.cluster[c]['node_list']: 
 685                      break 
 686              else: 
 687                  data = self.get_node(n).to_string() 
 688                  graph.append(data + ';\n') 
 689          # process edges 
 690          for e in self.edge_attr: 
 691              if e in processed_edges: 
 692                  continue 
 693              data = self.edge_to_string(e) 
 694              graph.append(data + ';\n') 
 695          graph.append( '}\n' ) 
 696          return ''.join(graph)
